[[File:Al-Kirmani, Commentary on 'Causes and symptoms' Wellcome L0013850.jpg|140px|thumbnail|Al-Kirmani, Commentary on 'Causes and symptoms']]
'''Abu al-Hakam al-Kirmani''' ({{lang-ar|أبو الحكم الكرماني}}; d. 1066 CE) was a prominent philosopher and scholar from the Muslim [[al-Andalus]]. A student of [[Maslamah Ibn Ahmad al-Majriti]], he was a [[Neoplatonic]] advocate, and seen as an influence on [[Ibn 'Arabi]], but he also wrote extensively on [[geometry]] and [[logic]]. His exact date of death is not known as he fled to [[Morocco]] in the twelfth century. It is possible that it was he who returned to al-Andalus with the [[Epistles of the Brethren of Purity]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Al-Andalusi|first=Sa`id|author-link=Said Al-Andalusi|title=Science in the medieval world : book of the Categories of nations|year=1996|publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]|isbn=0292704690|editors=Sema`an I. Salem, Alok Kumar|page=65}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Fakhry|first=Majid|title=A short introduction to Islamic philosophy, theology and mysticism|year=1997|publisher=Oneworld|isbn=1851681345|page=85}}</ref>
