{{pp|small=yes}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox writer | name = Wahiduddin Khan | image = maulanawahiduddin.jpg | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1925|01|01|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Azamgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[British India|India]] | occupation = Islamic spiritual leader, speaker and author | genre = [[Islamic literature]] | notableworks = [[Tazkirul Quran]] }}
'''Wahiduddin Khan''' (born 1 January 1925), known with the honorific '''Maulana''', is an [[Islam]]ic scholar and peace activist<ref>[http://www.indianmuslims.info/news/2007/oct/03/all_muslim_sects_should_agree_disagree_maulana_wahiduddin_khan.html All Muslim sects should agree to disagree: Maulana Wahiduddin Khan | Indian Muslims<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> known for having translated the Quran into contemporary English and for writing a commentary on the Quran.|<ref>http://www.goodword.net/read_quran_online.aspx A new translation of the Quran by Maulana Wahiduddin Khan</ref> His televised lectures have appeared on ETV Urdu, Zee Salaam, Bridges TV, ITV, ARY Digital, QTV, Aaj TV, etc.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.goodword.net/maulana_wahiduddin_khan.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 September 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103092254/http://www.goodword.net/maulana_wahiduddin_khan.aspx |archive-date=3 January 2010 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>
He has received, among others, the Demiurgus Peace International Award, under the patronage of the former Soviet President [[Mikhail Gorbachev]]; India's third-highest civilian honor, the [[Padma Bhushan]], in January 2000<ref>Tamara Sonn & Mary Williamsburg, (2004), ''A Brief History of Islam'', Blackwell. {{ISBN|1-4051-0902-5}}.</ref>; the National Citizens' Award, presented by [[Mother Teresa]] and the [[Rajiv Gandhi National Sadbhavana Award]] (2009).<ref>{{cite news |title=Muslim scholar gets Sadhbhavana Award|url=http://www.sify.com/news/muslim-scholar-gets-sadhbhavana-award-news-national-kiuvkdbhgdg.html |publisher=[[Sify.com]] |date=2010-08-20 }}</ref> He was conferred with the Sayyidina Imam Al Hassan Ibn Ali Peace Award (2015) in Abu Dhabi.{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}
==Early life== Khan was born in Village Badharia, in district [[Azamgarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]] in 1925.<ref>[http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/insights/maulana_wahiduddin_index.html Maulana Wahiduddin Khan]</ref> He graduated from a seminary of traditional Islamic learning. Like [[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi]], [[Israr Ahmed]] and [[ Naeem Siddiqui]], Khan also remained in close touch with [[Amin Ahsan Islahi]] and [[Syed Abul Ala Maududi]] (1903–1979) before opening an Islamic Center in [[Delhi]] in 1970.<ref>[[Javed Ahmad Ghamidi#Interaction with other Islamic scholars]]</ref>{{Better source|reason=per WP:CIRCULAR|date=May 2017}}
He joined the [[Jamaat-e-Islami]] in 1949. He quit it fifteen years later, arguing that Maududi had overly politicized Islam. He set out his ideas in his book, ''Tabeer kee Ghalati'' (The Error in Interpretation).{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}
==Publications== The ''Ar-risala'' (The Message) [[Urdu language|Urdu]] magazine was started in 1976 consisting of almost entirely his articles and writing. An [[English language|English]] edition of the magazine was started in February 1984 and a [[Hindi language|Hindi]] version in December 1990. His articles include 'Hijacking&nbsp;— A Crime',<ref>[http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/insights/insight20000215a.html Hijacking - A Crime<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> 'Rights of Women in Islam',<ref>[http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/insights/insight20000215b.html Rights of Women in Islam<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> 'The Concept of Charity in Islam'<ref>[http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/insights/insight20000330a.html The Concept of Charity in Islam<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and 'The Concept of Jihad'.<ref>[http://www.jammu-kashmir.com/insights/insight20000223a.html The Concept of Jihad<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> He has written a book on the issue of blasphemy from a dissenting perspective. It was banned in Punjab, the most populous province in [[Pakistan]], on 26 October 1998.{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}}
==Outlook== Many traditional Islamic scholars find Khan's outlook and opinions distasteful. Some of them have even dubbed him a fitna (source of strife).{{Citation needed|date= January 2018}} His advice to Muslims has been to not treat unpleasant or unwanted situations as problems as this would only yield negative results.<ref>[http://www.milligazette.com/Archives/15032002/1503200247.htm Analysis of the writings of Maulana Wahiduddin Khan - i, The Milli Gazette, Vol. 3 No. 6<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>
==List of selected works== He is the author of many books on Islam and modernity,<ref>Ayesha Jalal, ''Partisans of Allah: Jihad in South Asia'', Harvard University Press (2009), p. 266</ref> including:<ref>[http://www.astrolabe.com/contributor/246/Maulana_Wahiduddin_Khan.html Maulana Wahiduddin Khan - 17 products available]</ref>
* ''The Prophet of Peace'' * ''The Quran: A New Translation'' * ''A Treasury of the Quran'' * ''[[Tazkirul Quran]]'' * ''Indian Muslims: The Need for a Positive Outlook'' * ''Introducing Islam: A Simple Introduction to Islam'' * ''Islam Rediscovered: Discovering Islam From its Original Sources'' * ''Islam and Peace'' * ''Islam: Creator of the Modern Age'' * ''Words of the Prophet Muhammad'' * ''The Issue of Blasphemy''
